5000|$|Others, though—most notably President Lyndon B. Johnson—believed {{that certain}} types of {{unclassified}} government information should nonetheless remain secret. Notwithstanding the White House's opposition, Congress expanded Section 3 of the Administrative Procedure Act as a standalone measure in 1966 to further standardize the publication of government records, consistent {{with the belief that}} the people have the [...] "right to know" [...] about them. The Privacy Act of 1974 was passed as a <b>countervailing</b> <b>measure</b> to ensure the security of government documents increasingly kept on private citizens.|$|R
